<h4 class="heading"><span class="type">Paragraph</span></h4>
<p>To look at linear drag, let’s look at the case of a grain of sand of mass <span class="process-math">\(m\)</span> descending in water.  To model this, let <span class="process-math">\(y(t)\)</span> be distance the sand has fallen (so the positive <span class="process-math">\(y\)</span> axis is pointing downward), with <span class="process-math">\(y(0)=0\)</span> representing the surface of the water.  If we draw a diagram of the sand, there are three forces we need to consider: the weight of the object, the buoyancy of the object, and the drag.</p>
<span class="incontext"><a href="section-4.html#p-49" class="internal">in-context</a></span>
